1 AN ACT concerning municipalities; enacting the Kansas municipal
2 employee whistleblower act; establishing legal protections for certain
3 municipal employees who report or disclose unlawful or dangerous
4 conduct; providing an administrative appeal process for
5 municipalities.
6
7 Be it enacted by the Legislature of the State of Kansas:
8 Section 1. (a) This section shall be known and may be cited as the
9 Kansas municipal employee whistleblower act.
10 (b) As used in this section:
11 (1) "Auditing agency" means:
12 (A) The legislative post auditor;
13 (B) any employee of the division of post audit;
14 (C) any firm performing audit services pursuant to a contract with the
15 post auditor;
16 (D) any state agency or federal agency or authority performing
17 auditing or other oversight activities under authority of any provision of
18 law authorizing such activities; or
19 (E) the inspector general established under K.S.A. 75-7427, and
20 amendments thereto.
21 (2) "Disciplinary action" means any dismissal, demotion, transfer,
22 reassignment, suspension, reprimand, warning of possible dismissal or
23 withholding of work.
24 (3) "Malfeasance" means unlawful conduct committed by any
25 member of the governing body of a municipality or any officer or
26 other employee thereof.
27 (4) "Misappropriation" means the unauthorized or unlawful
28 expenditure or transfer of moneys held by a municipality.
29 (5) "Municipality" means any county, city or unified school district or
30 any office, department, division, board, commission, bureau, agency or
31 unit thereof.

HB 2160—Am. by SCW 2
1 (c) No supervisor or appointing authority of any municipality shall
2 prohibit any of the following or take any disciplinary action against an
3 employee of such municipality because such employee:
4 (1) Discussed the operations of the municipality or other matters of
5 public concern, including matters relating to the public health, safety and
6 welfare either specifically or generally, with any member of the legislature
7 or any auditing agency;
8 (2) reported a violation of state or federal law, municipal resolution or
9 ordinance or any rules and regulations adopted pursuant such law,
10 resolution or ordinance to any person, agency or organization;
11 (3) failed to give notice to the supervisor or appointing authority prior
12 to making any report described in paragraph (2); or
13 (4) disclosed malfeasance or other misappropriation of moneys held
14 by such municipality to any person, agency or organization; or
15 (5) disclosed a substantial and specific danger to public health or
16 safety to any person, agency or organization.
17 (d) This section shall not be construed to:
18 (1) Prohibit a supervisor or appointing authority from requiring that
19 an employee inform the supervisor or appointing authority regarding
20 legislative or auditing agency requests for information submitted to such
21 municipality or the substance of testimony made, or to be made, by the
22 employee to legislators or the auditing agency on behalf of such
23 municipality;
24 (2) permit an employee to leave the employee's assigned work areas
25 during normal work hours without following applicable rules and
26 regulations and policies pertaining to employee leave unless the employee
27 is requested by a legislator or legislative committee to appear before a
28 legislative committee or by an auditing agency to appear at a meeting with
29 officials of the auditing agency;
30 (3) authorize an employee to represent the employee's personal
31 opinions as the opinions of such municipality; or
32 (4) prohibit disciplinary action of an employee who discloses
33 information that:
34 (A) The employee knows to be false or that the employee discloses
35 with reckless disregard for the truth or falsity of such information or due
36 to a corrupt motive rather than a good faith concern for a wrongful
37 activity;
38 (B) the employee knows to be exempt from required disclosure under
39 the open records act; or
40 (C) is confidential or privileged under state or federal law or court
41 rule.
42 (e) (1) {Except for officers or employees eligible to administratively
43 appeal disciplinary actions pursuant to paragraph (2), }any officer or

